8472. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 44214785
T1  - Clinical follow-up of medical and surgical treatment of polycystic ovary syndrome in adolescents: North Jordan study
A1  - Jallad M.F.
A1  - Al-Rimawi H.S.
A1  - Bertelloni S.
A1  - Obeidat B.
A1  - Zayed F. 
Y1  - 2006//
N2  - Objective. To evaluate the results of medical and surgical treatment in adolescents with polycystic ovary syndrome. Materials and methods. Clinical data of 158 patients (age 14-21 years) with polycystic ovary syndrome, treated between January 2000 and December 2003 at Princess Badeea and King Abdullah Teaching Hospitals, were collected in a standardized way. Results. Fifty-one of these patients were obese; the majority (93%) achieved a body mass index <= 25 within 6-12 months after the initial visit, by dietary treatment. All patients who had menstrual irregularities (n = 147) responded to hormonal treatment, and their cycle became regular with normal menstrual blood loss within 3 months after starting treatment. The sixty-seven patients who presented with hirsutism (88%) responded to hormonal treatment, achieving satisfactory results within 6-12 months of treatment. Of the 13 infertile patients present in the group, nine (69%) became pregnant on either ovulation induction or laparoscopic ovarian drilling. Conclusion. Hormonal treatment is effective in restoring regular menstrual cycles and in treating most adolescents with hirsutism. Infertile young patients with polycystic ovary disease respond well to ovulation induction and ovarian drilling.
