8496. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 44755508
T1  - Marked insulin resistance in pregnancy
A1  - Evans K.M.
A1  - Millward B.A. 
Y1  - 2006//
N2  - Normal pregnancy is a state of relative insulin resistance, with gestational diabetes (GDM) developing in up to 10% of women in the UK. Both obesity and polycystic ovarian syndrome predispose to GDM; the underlying insulin resistance may necessitate large insulin doses and present challenges for antenatal diabetes management. We report on a lady with polycystic ovarian syndrome and subfertility, initially treated with metformin, who developed GDM and marked insulin resistance. Throughout her pregnancy, insulin requirements escalated considerably, to over 5000 units. Despite concerted efforts, antenatal glycaemic targets were not reached, and a macrosomic infant was born at 36 weeks. Maternal post-partum, testing has confirmed type 2 diabetes mellitus. Copyright © 2006 John Wiley & Sons, Ltd.
