8590. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 43493870
T1  - Clinical outcomes of surgical treatment of PCO syndrome
A1  - Szczepanska M.
A1  - Skrzypczak J. 
Y1  - 2005//
N2  - Background: The aim of this study was to present the outcomes of surgical treatment in women with PCO syndrome. Material/Methods: The analysis included 76 women diagnosed with PCO syndrome and treated in the Division of Reproduction in Poznan form September 1997 to December 2004. The surgery was based on either wedge resection of the ovaries during laparotomy, wedge resection with harmonic knife or electrocautery during laparoscopy, monopolar and bipolar diathermy. Five patients were excluded from the study because they decided not to have children shortly after the surgery. Result(s): Among 71 women surgically treated for PCOs, 63 (88.7%) have had regular cycles; 54(76%) achieved pregnancy, including 35 women (49%) getting pregnant spontaneously within the first year after the operation, the other 19 (27%) within 54 months after the operation. Forty five (83%) among 54 patients who achieved pregnancy after surgical treatment of PCO, delivered healthy newborns, 2(3.5%) delivered prematurely and in 4(7%) the pregnancy ended with fetal demise in the first trimester; further 3 patients are in I, II, III trimester of pregnancy, respectively. The most common complication of pregnancy was pregnancy-induced hypertension (7%), gestational diabetes (4%) and cervical incompetence (4%). Conclusion(s): Based on our analysis, it might be stated that the surgery in infertile women diagnosed with PCOs, especially with the use of harmonic knife and electrocautry leads to high percentage of ovulatory cycles and pregnancies, with reduction in the number of miscarriages. The positive effect of the surgery continues for many years. No increased rates of complications are observed during pregnancy.
