T1  - Prevention of ovarian hyperstimulation syndrome by early aspiration of small follicles in hyper-responsive patients with polycystic ovaries during assisted reproductive treatment cycles
A1  - Oyawoye O.A.
A1  - Chander B.
A1  - Hunter J.
A1  - Gadir A.A. 
Y1  - 2005//
N2  - Objective: This study was designed to assess the efficacy of early aspiration of small follicles (EASF) in preventing moderate hyperstimulation syndrome (OHSS) in women with polycystic ovaries who experienced excessive ovarian response during the assisted reproductive treatment cycles (ART). Study Design: EASF was undertaken transvaginally during 15 in vitro fertilization (IVF) or intracytoplasmic sperm injection (ICSI women with polycystic ovaries who produced more than 20 small follicles during the early part of the cycle. A minimum of 10 small Outcomes: None of the patients developed moderate or severe OHSS. There were 9 intrauterine pregnancies (60 %) and 1 ectopic Conclusion(s): EASF 4 to 7 days after starting gonadotropin injections prevented moderate and severe OHSS in susceptible patients polycystic ovaries and resulted in a high pregnancy rate. Larger studies are needed to verify these promising results. © 2005 Medscape.
