AN  - 35190608
ID  - 12394876 [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12394876]
T1  - End-tidal CO2-derived values during emergency trauma surgery correlated with outcome: A prospective study
A1  - Tyburski J.G.
A1  - Collinge J.D.
A1  - Wilson R.F.
A1  - Carlin A.M.
A1  - Albaran R.G.
A1  - Steffes C.P. 
Y1  - 2002//
N2  - Background: The purpose of this study was to determine whether end-tidal carbon dioxide (PETCO2) derived variables assist in evaluating the adequacy of resuscitation during emergency surgery for trauma. Method(s): This was a prospective study of end-tidal derived variables and outcome in 106 trauma patients in an urban Level I trauma center. Result(s): The patients who lived (compared with those who died) had higher final end-tidal PCO2 levels, lower arterial-end tidal CO2 differences (Pa-ET)CO2, and a decreased alveolar dead space ratio (p < 0.001). The best survival rates were with a PETCO2 > 27 mm Hg, a (Pa-ET)CO2 <= 9 mm Hg, and 96% (56 of 58) for an alveolar dead space ratio <= 0.20 (p < 0.001). An inappropriately high or "excess PaCO2" also correlated with a decreased (Pa-ET)CO2 and poorer prognosis. If, after the initial resuscitation, the PETCO2-derived values did not achieve these "optimal" levels, survival was significantly reduced. Conclusion(s): During emergency trauma surgery, the PETCO2 and its derived values help to predict outcome and may be used to identify patients needing more aggressive resuscitation.
