A1  - Tulandi T. 
Y1  - 2002//
N2  - Objectives: To evaluate the response of transforming growth factor-beta (TGF-beta) to glucose ingestion in anovulatory women with polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS). Design(s): Prospective study. Patient(s): 10 anovulatory women with PCOS and 6 women without PCOS. Intervention(s): Blood sampling before and 120 minutes after glucose ingestion. Main Outcome Measure(s): Serum TGF-beta responses to glucose ingestion. Result(s): Serum insulin levels after glucose ingestion in PCOS women were higher than in women without PCOS (1619.0 +/- 260.9 and 552.7 +/- 105.1 pmol/L). There was a significant decline in total TGF-beta levels before and after glucose ingestion in women with and without PCOS. The bioactive TGF-beta levels after glucose ingestion were significantly lower in women with PCOS, but not in those without PCOS. The baseline serum insulin levels were not correlated with active TGF-beta (r: 0.29) or total TGF-beta levels (r: 0.28), but basal glucose and total TGF-beta levels were significantly correlated (r: 0.74, P <0.001). Conclusion(s): Glucose ingestion decreases serum TGF-beta levels. The decline in bioactive TGF-beta levels suggests that not only TGF-beta secretion is decreased, but the activation of TGF-beta is also weakened by glucose ingestion. To the best of our knowledge, this is the first report of a change in TGF-beta induced by glucose in human.
