T1  - Improvement in insulin sensitivity followed by ovulation and pregnancy in a woman with polycystic ovary syndrome who was treated with rosiglitazone
A1  - Cataldo N.A.
A1  - Abbasi F.
A1  - McLaughlin T.L.
A1  - Lamendola C.
A1  - Reaven G.M. 
Y1  - 2001//
N2  - Objective: To determine the metabolic and reproductive effectiveness of rosiglitazone in polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS). Design(s): Case report. Setting(s): Academic clinical practice and General Clinical Research Center.Patient(s): A 25-year-old woman with PCOS. Intervention(s): Rosiglitazone maleate, 4 mg daily for 5 months until conception. Main Outcome Measure(s): Insulin sensitivity by steady-state plasma glucose technique; serum androgens, progesterone, and hCG; and pelvic ultrasound images. Result(s): Rosiglitazone treatment for 5 months improved insulin sensitivity, lowered serum free testosterone, and resulted in spontaneous ovulation and conception. Conclusion(s): Rosiglitazone is a promising insulin sensitizer for treatment of PCOS. Clinical trials are warranted. Copyright © 2001 American Society for Reproductive Medicine.
