9190. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 32703820
ID  - 11476779 [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11476779]
T1  - Lactational amenorrhea/anovulation and some of their determinants: A comparison of well-nourished and undernourished women
A1  - Wasalathanthri S.
A1  - Tennekoon K.H. 
Y1  - 2001//
N2  - Objective: To study the effect of maternal nutritional status and some other possible determinants on lactational amenorrhea/anovulation. Design(s): Prospective matched-pairs study. Setting(s): Postpartum wards and community and academic settings. Patient(s): Thirty matched pairs of otherwise healthy, well-nourished (body mass index >= 26.00 kg/m2) and undernourished (body mass index <= 19.00 kg/m2) postpartum women were selected. Intervention(s): Infant feeding pattern was recorded weekly, and infant weights, maternal body mass index, and maternal PRL levels were estimated every 4 weeks until resumption of menstruation. Ovulatory activity was determined using urinary estrone and pregnanediol glucuronide concentrations. Main Outcome Measure(s): Time of resumption of menstruation, regular and ovulatory. Result(s): Well-nourished women resumed regular menstruation significantly earlier than undernourished women but resumed ovulatory menstruation at almost the same time. Undernourished women had fewer anovulatory cycles preceding first postpartum ovulation and a higher prevalence of formula feeding. Effect of body mass index on lactational amenorrhea became nonsignificant when nonintroduction of formula feeds, maternal age, and socioeconomic status were controlled for. Conclusion(s): Improved maternal nutritional status has no significant effect on fertility: ovulation is not advanced despite early resumption of regular menstruation. © 2001 by American Society for Reproductive Medicine.
