9207. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 34032069
T1  - Metformin reverses anovulation in hyperinsulinemic patients with polycystic ovary syndrome
A1  - Rull K.
A1  - Vali M. 
Y1  - 2001//
N2  - The aim of the study was to analyze therapeutic results of metformin an insulin sensitizing agent, in patients with polycystic ovary syndrome. Eighteen anovulatory patients with polycystic ovary syndrome were treated with 500 mg metformin twice daily. Ovulation was evaluated by Biocard ovulation test. When no ovulatory cycles occurred after 16-20 weeks, clomiphene, 50 mg twice daily for 5 days was introduced. Within a one-month period, five patients discontinued metformin therapy for various subjective reasons. The patients were lean (body mass index 21.6+/-4.5, normoinsulinemic, with elevated serum testosterone (5.2+/-2.4 mml/), LH/FSH ratio (3.15+/-3.9) and polycystic ovaries on ultrasonography. Among 13 patients treated with metformin for up to 18 months, spontaneous (n=10) or clomiphene induced (n = 1) ovulation occurred in 11 cases at 2-4 months of treatment. Conception and delivery occurred in three patients. At 4-6 months of treatment, mean serum testosterone decreased (from 5.33+/-2.50 to 2.33+/-2.04 mmol/), and the menstrual pattern normalized. No changes were observed in hirsutism, body mass index, arterial blood pressure, serum LH/FSH ratio, and other sex steroids. The patients from this group mostly were obese (body mass index 31.6+/-7.62), and showed higher hyperinsulinemia and lower LH/FSH ratio (2.33.+/-1.24) than those who discontinued metformin therapy. It is concluded that metformin reverses chronic anovulation and reduces hyperandrogenemia more efficiently in hyperinsulinemic patients with polycystic ovary syndrome.
