9269. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 32126883
T1  - Transvaginal ultrasonography and the evaluation of female infertility
A1  - Pierson R.A.
A1  - Olatunbosun O.A. 
Y1  - 2000//
N2  - Transvaginal high-resolution diagnostic ultrasonography has become the most important development in infertility investigation since the widespread application of radioimmunoassay techniques for the reproductively active hormones. The development of relatively high frequency (e.g., 5.0 MHz or 7.5 MHz), curvi-linear array transducers and colour-flow Doppler technology for transvaginal use has dramatically increased the resolution of images allowing detection of minute differences in the morphology of the female reproductive organs. Although transabdominal ultrasonography of the pelvis has been used for several years, the ability to place the transducer into the vaginal fornix, just a few millimetres from the organs of interest, yields unprecedented resolution for evaluation of the ovaries, oviducts and uterus. The vaginal approach to imaging the reproductive organs also obviates the need for a full bladder, thereby minimizing patient discomfort, and enhances acceptance of ultrasonographic examination by both the patient and the examiner.
